@node discl "Disclaimer"
@{fg shine}
 >>> DISCLAIMER
@{fg text}
 Both programs provided in this archive, @{"Magazine" link magaz} and @{"MagEdit" link medit}, do not come
 with any warranty of any kind!  They seem to be bug-free and shouldn't
 cause data loss or damage to any Amiga system.

 However, the @{"author" link autho} would like to protect himself (just a precaution) and
 therefore makes this statement:
@{i}
 "By using @{b}Magazine@{ub} or @{b}MagEdit@{ub}, the user agrees to take no legal actions
 against the author, both now and in the future, in the event that data loss
 or damage is suffered as a direct/indirect result of using said programs."
@{ui}
 You don't @{i}have@{ui} to agree with the above statement, but once you start either
 of them then your agreement is confirmed!  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node intro "Introduction"
@{fg shine}
 >>> INTRODUCTION
@{fg text}
 @{b}Magazine@{ub} is a program for distributing your own disk-based magazines.  It
 does so by exactly emulating a real-life paper magazine: it has pages that
 contain articles, and nothing more.  @{b}Magazine@{ub} does @{i}not@{ui} support animations,
 sounds, hypertext links, or any other fancy tricks like that.  There are
 plenty of magazine creation programs that can do all that for you, and you
 are welcome to find and use them.

 @{b}Magazine@{ub}'s charm lies in its simplicity.  Everyone knows how to read a real
 paper magazine, and thus they can easily learn to use and enjoy @{b}Magazine@{ub}
 almost instantly.  All you do is turn pages and read the articles.  :)  In
 fact, why not try it now by double-clicking the @{"Magazine" link magaz} icon?

 With this archive comes another program, called @{b}MagEdit@{ub}.  This is what you
 can use to actually create and edit your own magazines.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node requi "Requirements"
@{fg shine}
 >>> REQUIREMENTS
@{fg text}
 @{"Magazine" link magaz} and @{"MagEdit" link medit} require the following items to run:

  À Any Amiga running Workbench 2.04 or higher
  À ReqTools.library (click @{"here" link rtool} for more info)

 (Actually, @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} is @{i}not@{ui} required to run @{b}Magazine@{ub}, but rather
 @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub}-enhanced.  This means if someone tries to read your
 magazine and they @{i}don't@{ui} have @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} installed, they can still
 read it.  On the other hand, readers @{i}with@{ui} @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} installed will
 have a slightly-enhanced reading experience [busy pointers, centred help
 windows, etc]).

 No further requirements for @{b}Magazine@{ub} are necessary, but @{b}MagEdit@{ub} uses the
 Amiga's @{b}Ed@{ub} text editor which can usually be found in your boot drive's @{b}C@{ub}
 directory.  If the @{b}Ed@{ub} program isn't there, please copy it there from your
 Workbench installation disks before attempting to use @{b}MagEdit@{ub}.

 Strictly speaking, @{b}Ed@{ub} @{i}isn't@{ui} absolutely necessary, because you can edit your
 text stories with your own favourite text editor before importing them into
 your magazine.  However, if you want to edit your text stories from @{i}within@{ui}
 @{b}MagEdit@{ub} (ie: without leaving the program's screen), then you @{i}will@{ui} need to
 ensure that @{b}Ed@{ub} is in your boot drive's @{b}C@{ub} directory.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node amiga "Compatibility"
@{fg shine}
 >>> COMPATIBILITY
@{fg text}
 Firstly, I'll assume you've read the @{"requirements" link requi} section...?  Good!

 Okay, both @{"Magazine" link magaz} and @{"MagEdit" link medit} have only been tested on one Amiga, since
 that's all the @{"author" link autho} has access to.  It has the following configuration:

  À Amiga 1200, Workbench 3.1, AGA Chipset, 68020, 2 MB Chip, 4 MB Fast.

 Thus, the author can absolutely, positively, @{i}guarantee without question@{ui}
 that @{b}Magazine@{ub} and @{b}MagEdit@{ub} will run on such a system.  :)

 Anyway, if either program crashes on @{i}your@{ui} system, try the following:

  À Ensure @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} is installed on your @{i}original@{ui} Workbench disk.
  À Ensure the @{b}Courier font@{ub} is installed on your @{i}original@{ui} Workbench disk.
  À Boot from your original Workbench disk.
  À Run the offending program.

 The program @{i}should@{ui} now run without hassle.  It @{i}does@{ui} on the author's Amiga,
 when he performs the same four steps as above.  If you @{i}still@{ui} encounter
 problems, then I'm afraid it's not due to the program, but definitely due
 to something else you have installed which is clashing with it.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node rtool "ReqTools.library"
@{fg shine}
 >>> WHAT THE HECK IS "REQTOOLS.LIBRARY" ?
@{fg text}
 @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub} is what you might consider a "system enhancer" for your
 Amiga.  Basically, it's a file that many programs use that enable them to
 provide "requesters" of all shapes and sizes.  In fact, it's so popular
 that you might already have it installed in your system!

 If you run @{"Magazine" link magaz} and get an error message saying that @{b}ReqTools.library@{ub}
 is not installed, then unfortunately you don't have it yet.  You'll have to
 download it from Aminet: its name is @{b}ReqToolsUsr.lha@{ub} and it's found in the
 @{b}util/libs@{ub} directory.  Install it as soon as possible, because a great deal
 of Amiga software makes use of it these days.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node magaz "Using Magazine"
@{fg shine}
 >>> USING MAGAZINE
@{fg text}
 @{b}Magazine@{ub} is the program used to actually read and display your magazines.
 It's the program that you distribute for your readers to use that enables
 them to enjoy your work.
 
 Double-click the @{b}Magazine@{ub} icon and have a read of the example magazine that
 appears.  The program operates like a real-life paper magazine, so there
 isn't anything to be afraid of.  There's an @{b}Online Help@{ub} button to click if
 you get confused, but I doubt it.  To read @{i}more@{ui} of a long text file, just
 click the mouse in the @{i}bottom half@{ui} of the text to display more of the file.
 To go back to the @{i}start@{ui} of the text, click the @{i}top half@{ui} of it.  To move to
 a different page, either drag the slider bar to select the page, or click
 to the left or right of it to move one page back or forward.

 What you've just done is what your potential readers will do.  See how easy
 it is to present a good-looking magazine for them?  No longer do you have
 to stick with a cliche-ridden AmigaGuide mag with no graphics, or have to
 use some extremely complicated and memory-hungry mag creator!  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node medit "Using MagEdit"
@{fg shine}
 >>> USING MAG EDIT
@{fg text}
 @{b}MagEdit@{ub} is the program used for actually creating your magazines.  However,
 just like a real-life magazine, creating a magazine with @{b}MagEdit@{ub} requires
 quite a bit of forethought and planning.  In other words, you can't just
 "jump in" and start using @{b}MagEdit@{ub} straight away.  Think first, then act.

 Firstly, have a pen and notepad handy.  The format of your magazines is the
 following: You have an unlimited number of pages (with disk space being the
 only restriction), and up to 4 "article boxes" per page.  Each article box
 can hold one picture and/or one text story.  Then, in your notepad, number
 the top of each page as a magazine page number.  Decide what you are going
 to put on each page.  Basically, use the notepad to actually design your
 magazine layout, because trying to do this with @{b}MagEdit@{ub} will cause you some
 unnecessary hassles.  @{b}MagEdit@{ub} is only used to actually create your mag, and
 not to actually plan the layout.

 Once you have designed the layout in your notepad, the next step is create
 all the pictures you want to use.  Do this with any good paint program such
 as @{b}Brilliance@{ub}.  Pictures @{i}can't@{ui} be larger than @{b}310@{ub} pixels wide and @{b}75@{ub} pixels
 high.  There's a picture in this archive called @{b}SetupPic.iff@{ub} with which you
 can design your pictures: just draw @{i}inside@{ui} the yellow boxes and then cut
 them out as brushes to save as magazine pics.  Make sure you @{i}don't@{ui} change
 the palette's size or colours either, because then @{"Magazine" link magaz} won't display
 your pictures in the correct colours!

 Next, you can edit your text files that will be used in your magazine.
 These must @{i}not@{ui} have any lines that are longer than @{b}51@{ub} characters, so you
 must word wrap them first if they are.  @{b}MagEdit@{ub} can do the word wrapping
 for you, so if you choose this option, read on.  Otherwise, wrap the text
 yourself using any text editor and then read on.

 @{i}IMPORTANT:@{ui} @{b}MagEdit@{ub} will create a magazine in the @{i}same directory as itself.@{ui}
 Thus, to create a brand new magazine, drag the @{b}MagEdit@{ub} icon to a brand new
 directory @{i}first@{ui} and run it from there.

 Now it's time to tell @{b}MagEdit@{ub} where everything goes.  Start @{b}MagEdit@{ub} and
 look at the top of the window.  You'll see a row of buttons that are used
 to place pictures/text, define the page name, and other various things.
 Look now at the bottom two article boxes: they have a message that says
 @{b}(This box unavailable in this demo)@{ub}.  This is because @{b}MagEdit@{ub} is ShareWare,
 and you must @{"register" link share} if you intend to use it often.  In other words, if
 you don't register @{b}MagEdit@{ub}, you can only use it to edit the top two boxes
 of your pages.

 Okay, what @{"I'll" link autho} do now is take you step-by-step through re-designing page
 @{b}1@{ub} of the example magazine.  Make sure you have started @{b}MagEdit@{ub} from the
 @{i}same@{ui} directory as the @{b}Magazine@{ub} program, so that @{b}MagEdit@{ub} will be able to use
 the files there.

 You should already be at page @{b}1@{ub} if you have just started @{b}MagEdit@{ub}.  At the
 top of the screen you will see the top two boxes of the example magazine.
 Firstly, let's take a look at how the @{b}Clear Page@{ub} gadget works.  This gadget
 will clear (that is, delete) all the current page's pictures and text.  (If
 you want to keep the example mag's contents, copy them to another directory
 first).  Click the @{b}Clear Page@{ub} gadget and you are asked if you really want
 to delete all pictures/text.  Click the @{b}Yes@{ub} gadget and off they go!  :)

 Notice that the page no longer has a name.  To give it one, just click the
 @{b}Define Name@{ub} gadget and enter a name.  Easy!

 Now let's re-create the example magazine.  At the top-right of the window
 are 4 gadgets labelled @{b}Add P@{ub}, @{b}Add T@{ub}, @{b}Del P@{b}, @{b}Del T@{ub}.  These are used to add a
 picture and text, or delete a picture and text, accordingly.  Click the
 @{b}Add P@{ub} gadget.  You are now asked which box you want to put the picture in.
 Click @{b}1@{ub} to specify the @{b}above-left@{ub} box.  You are now given a file requester
 to select the picture you want to add.  Select the IFF picture file called
 @{b}AboveLeft.iff@{ub}.  Instantly, the picure is loaded and stored into page 1 in
 the above-left box.

 Now let's add the "contents" text to the above-right box.  Click the gadget
 labelled @{b}Add T@{ub} and then click @{b}2@{ub} to specify the @{b}above-right@{ub} box.  Then, via
 the file requester, select the file called @{b}AboveRight.txt@{ub}.  Now you will be
 asked if you wish to @{b}word wrap@{ub} this file.  If you have already done so,
 click @{b}No@{ub} and the text will simply go into the box as it stands.  Otherwise,
 click @{b}Yes@{ub} and you will be asked to specify the maximum column number.  At
 this point, one of two steps must be taken:

  (1) If you @{i}don't@{ui} have a picture in the box, click @{b}Ok@{ub} to accept the default
      value of @{b}51@{ub} and thus wrap and add the text.  You can ignore step 2.

  (2) If you @{i}do@{ui} have a picture in the box, click @{b}Ok@{ub} to accept the calculated
      value supplied.  Then, you will be asked to specify a margin size.
      Again, just click @{b}Ok@{ub} to accept the calculated value supplied.  Now the
      text is added next to the picture.  If the text does @{i}not@{ui} overwrite the
      picture, then all is well and you can consider the box complete.  But
      if the text @{i}does@{ui} overwrite the picture, you should manually trim the
      word wrap and margin settings.  To do this, add the text again by
      clicking the @{b}Add T@{ub} button and selecting the box.  Select the text file
      with the requester.  Click @{b}Yes@{ub} to the word wrap option, BUT... this
      time @{i}subtract@{ui} @{b}1@{ub} from the calculated value.  Then, when asked for the
      margin size, @{i}add@{ui} @{b}1@{ub} to the calculated value.  The text will then be
      added to the box but this time @{i}shouldn't@{ui} overwrite the picture.

 If you did @{i}not@{ui} edit the text file yourself, the word wrap option will no
 doubt leave some of your text in need of slight adjustments.  To edit text
 that's been placed in a box, click the @{b}Edit@{ub} gadget and specify the box.
 Now the Workbench screen will be brought to the front of your monitor and
 the text file will be loaded into @{b}Ed@{ub} for editing.  Fix up any necessary
 adjustments and save the fixed file by pressing (in sequence) @{b}ESC@{ub}, @{b}X@{ub}, and
 @{b}Return@{ub}.  The @{b}MagEdit@{ub} screen will now come to the front and the fixed text
 file re-loaded into the box.

 At this point, you know almost everything there is about using @{b}MagEdit@{ub}.
 There's only two things left to explain: how to delete a picture/text from
 a box, and how to edit a different page.

 Deleting a picture or text from a box is done exactly the same way as you
 added them, except you click the @{b}Del P@{ub} and @{b}Del T@{ub} gadgets instead of the
 @{b}Add P@{ub} and @{b}Add T@{ub} ones.

 To start editing another page, click the @{b}Edit Other@{ub} gadget.  Now enter the
 new page number.  If such a page doesn't exist, @{b}MagEdit@{ub} gives you the
 option of making it or selecting another.  If you decide to make it, be
 sure you @{i}really@{ui} want to, because @{b}MagEdit@{ub} doesn't allow you to delete pages!
 That's why you should prepare your magazine layout first on paper.

 If you want to re-load the current page for some reason, perhaps to refresh
 its contents, just click @{b}Edit Other@{ub} and then just press @{b}Return@{ub}.

 When your magazine is done, you need to specify the @{b}Issue Data@{ub} by editing
 the reader program's (ie: @{"Magazine" link magaz}) ToolTypes.  Click @{"here" link issue} to read how.
 Then the last step is to @{"distribute" link distr} your completed mag to the people.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node style "Text Styles"
@{fg shine}
 >>> TEXT STYLES
@{fg text}
 The text files you put in your magazines can be enhanced with the following
 @{i}style parameters@{ui}.  Each parameter must be on a single line of its own and
 can't be combined with any other.

 @{u}Parameter:@{uu}    @{u}Function:@{uu}

 ;             A commented line in your file.  Any line that starts with a
               semi-colon is @{i}not@{ui} displayed when reading your magazine.

 @cen=1        Turns centering of subsequent lines @{i}on@{ui} until further notice.

 @cen=0        Turns centering of subsequent lines @{i}off@{ui} until further notice.

 @mar=<1-51>   Margin setting.  Each line is indented the specified number
               of spaces in its box until further notice.  Usually used in
               conjunction with a picture to stop the text overwriting it.

 @sty=<style>  Style of text.  The number here depends on how you want each
               subsequent line of text to appear until further notice.

               The 4 style values supported are:

               0 = Turn off all styles and use normal text.
               1 = Turn on @{u}underlined@{uu} style.
               2 = Turn on @{b}bold@{ub} style.
               4 = Turn on @{i}italic@{ui} style.

               To combine any styles, add the values together.  For example,
               to have underlined and italicised text, use the value 5.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node issue "Issue Data"
@{fg shine}
 >>> DEFINING YOUR MAGAZINE'S ISSUE DATA
@{fg text}
 Every magazine has an issue date and/or volume number, and a name.  When
 you have finished creating your magazine with @{"MagEdit" link medit}, you have to give
 these issue details to the reader program (@{"Magazine" link magaz}) so that your readers
 know what they're reading and the issue.  This is done by adding three icon
 ToolTypes to @{b}Magazine@{ub}'s icon.

 @{u}ToolType:@{uu}         @{u}What It Does:@{uu}

 NAME=<mag name>   Holds the name of your mag.  It's usually best to have
                   this in upper-case letters, so it stands out when the
                   reader first "opens" your mag.

 ISSUE=<issue#>    Holds the issue number of your mag.  This is any number
                   that identifies this mag from a previous issue.

 DATE=<date>       Holds the date release of your mag.  This can be any date
                   format, so you could use @{b}April 1997@{ub} or @{b}May 20 1997@{ub}, or in
                   fact any date information you desire!

 All three of these ToolTypes @{i}are@{ui} important and @{i}should@{ui} be specified.  But
 if you don't, the appropriate data will be set to @{b}Unknown@{ub} when the reader
 first "opens" your mag.

 If you don't know how to edit @{b}Magazine@{ub}'s ToolTypes, all you do is: Click
 once on @{b}Magazine@{ub}'s icon, then select @{b}Information...@{ub} from the Workbench
 @{b}Icon@{ub} menu.  A window will appear, and at the bottom-left of it are three
 gadgets called @{b}New@{ub}, @{b}Del@{ub} and @{b}Save@{ub}.  Click @{b}New@{ub} to add a ToolType, click @{b}Del@{ub}
 to delete one, and click @{b}Save@{ub} to save the icon with the edited ToolTypes.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node troub "TroubleShooting"
@{fg shine}
 >>> TROUBLESHOOTING
@{fg text}
 Below is a series of questions-and-answers that you may have when creating
 a magazine.  If they still don't help, contact the @{"author" link autho}.


 À @{i}My text files are getting chopped and not showing the whole lines.@{ui}

   You haven't word wrapped the file to 51 characters or less.  This is done
   for you when using @{"MagEdit" link medit}.  If you didn't use @{b}MagEdit@{ub}, then it's up to
   you to work out a way to wrap the text.


 À @{i}I just added a picture to a box that already had text, and now the text
   is overwriting it.@{ui}

   When combining a picture and text in a box, always add the picture @{i}first@{ui}
   and the text @{i}last@{ui}.  This is so the text knows how to wrap itself around
   the picture.  After all, how can text avoid a picture when the picture
   doesn't exist in the box yet?  :)


 À @{i}I added a picture to a box and then the text (to fix the above problem),
   but my text still overwrites the picture.@{ui}

   You need to trim the @{"margin" link style} setting in your text.  Trimming is explained
   in the @{"MagEdit" link medit} tutorial; @{i}don't@{ui} trim it by altering the margin setting
   alone because the text lines will then be longer than 51 characters!


 À @{i}The text styles don't work and are showing up in my text.@{ui}

   Text styles only work if they are on a line @{i}by themselves@{ui} and start at
   the @{i}leftmost@{ui} position of the line (ie: no spaces before them).


 À @{i}You said pictures are always placed at the left of a box, but a picture
   of Claudia on page 3 is in the middle.  How?@{ui}

   A trick of the trade.  :)  It's not that hard to work out, but if you're
   really stumped, load the picture into a paint program to find out.


 À @{i}My pictures have all the wrong colours when in the magazine, but looked
   fine when I first drew them.@{ui}

   You didn't draw them with the palette that @{"Magazine" link magaz} uses.  Load the IFF
   picture called @{b}SetupPic.iff@{ub} and draw your pictures @{i}inside@{ui} the yellow
   boxes.  Then cut them out as brushes and save them as your pictures, and
   you'll find that the colours will now be correct.  Alternatively, load
   the incorrect picture as a brush into the paint program @{i}after@{ui} you have
   loaded @{b}SetupPic.iff@{ub}.  Then select your program's @{b}Remap Brush@{ub} option and
   your picture @{i}might@{ui} now be coloured correctly.  If so, save it!  :)


 À @{i}How do I put a colour photo into the magazine like you did with Claudia?@{ui}

   You need to use an image-processing program like @{b}ImageFX@{ub} or @{b}ADPro@{ub}.  Load
   the photo into it and convert it to greyscale, or whatever option the
   program uses to turn a colour picture into a grey one.  Then, render the
   picture to what is called @{b}Hires@{ub} (either PAL or NTSC).  Make sure you
   also render using only @{b}16@{ub} colours, and nothing else.  Save the resultant
   image to disk and load it as a brush as mentioned in the above previous
   question.  Select @{b}Remap Brush@{ub} and the image @{i}should@{ui} be colour-corrected
   and ready for saving and thus importing into your magazine.  If all this
   sounds too hard, well, it's the only way to do it, so you'll have to work
   it out I'm afraid.  There's no other way I can help you, sorry.  :(
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node distr "Distribution"
@{fg shine}
 >>> DISTRIBUTION OF YOUR MAGAZINE
@{fg text}
 Once you have completed your magazine, and you're 100% sure that it's fine
 with no problems occurring (eg: text overwriting pictures), then it's time
 to distribute it to the masses!  :)

 If you followed the @{"MagEdit" link medit} tutorial correctly, you'll know that your mag
 is made up of a directory for each page, and you should have created a new
 directory before starting your mag so that it only contains mag data.  If
 you didn't, then I highly suggest that you create a new directory somewhere
 and copy your page directories to it.

 The next step is to remove the @{b}MagEdit@{ub} program from this dir, since you
 don't want it to be distributed with your mag.  Just drag it somewhere else
 where it's nice and safe for the future.

 Okay, so now you've got a clean directory with only your page dirs inside.
 Drag the @{"Magazine" link magaz} icon into this directory, and make sure you've added the
 mag's @{"Issue Data" link issue} ToolTypes to it.  Now you'll have a directory structure
 that looks like so:

 Magazine
 Magazine.info
    1 <dir>
    2 <dir>
    . <dir>
    . <dir>

 As you can see, the directory has only the magazine reader program and your
 page directories.  This is all we want for distribution!  Anything else is
 just extraneous garbage which adds bulk to your mag's size.  Anyway, once
 the above is clean and done, you can archive your mag's main directory and
 distribute it!  Suggestion: Upload it to Aminet in the @{b}docs/mags@{ub} directory,
 where everyone will find it.

 Good luck, and don't forget to E-Mail @{"me" link autho} an issue!  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node summa "Design Summary"
@{fg shine}
 >>> DESIGN SUMMARY: FROM CREATION TO DISTRIBUTION
@{fg text}
 Here is a checklist of all steps involved in creating and distributing a
 magazine.  If you follow these, @{i}in strict order@{ui}, you will be fine:

  @{b}1@{ub}  Write in a notepad what will go where (ie: pics/text) on each page.
  @{b}2@{ub}  Draw @{i}all@{ui} pictures and edit @{i}all@{ui} text for the @{i}whole@{ui} magazine.
  @{b}3@{ub}  Create a new disk directory so your new magazine will be empty.
  @{b}4@{ub}  Drag the @{b}MagEdit@{ub} icon into this directory and start it.
  @{b}5@{ub}  Select the page number to edit by clicking the @{b}Edit Other@{ub} gadget.
  @{b}6@{ub}  Add the pictures to the desired boxes on the page.
  @{b}7@{ub}  Add the text to the desired boxes on the page.
  @{b}8@{ub}  Name the page.
  @{b}9@{ub}  If you need to edit/add another page, go back to step @{b}5@{ub}.
 @{b}10@{ub}  Drag the @{b}MagEdit@{ub} icon @{i}out of@{ui} the mag's directory.
 @{b}11@{ub}  Drag the @{b}Magazine@{ub} icon @{i}into@{ui} the mag's directory.
 @{b}12@{ub}  Edit the @{b}Magazine@{ub} icon's ToolTypes with the @{b}Issue Data@{ub} info.
 @{b}13@{ub}  Distribute your magazine!  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node restr "Restrictions"
@{fg shine}
 >>> RESTRICTIONS
@{fg text}
 The following are what you can't do with @{b}Magazine@{ub} at the moment:

  À You can't have a line of text longer than 51 characters.  Yes, it's an
    absolute bitch, but what can I do?  The concept behind @{b}Magazine@{ub} is to
    have 4 article boxes per page, and if they all supported 80 characters
    then you would need a screen width of more than 960 pixels (assuming
    that each character is 6 pixels wide).  Sure, I could use a much smaller
    font, but don't you agree that it's small enough already (Courier 11) ?

  À You can't enjoy AGA graphics.  Shoot me.  :)  I thought long and hard
    about this one, and decided that implementing an AGA screen would stop
    ECS users from reading your magazines.  After all, ECS doesn't display
    more than 16 colours in Hi-Res.  So while it's nice to dream about AGA
    colour, it's not going to happen.  The aim of a magazine is to get the
    widest readership possible, and forcing people to miss out due to only
    having ECS is a crime.

  À You can't change the screen palette.  Again, shoot me.  The decision was
    made that the 16 colours would be mostly greys, to make incorporating
    photos easy, with a few extra "primary" colours thrown in.  The palette
    used is extremely versatile, and with careful dithering you can get a
    good range of colours.  However, I may allow changing some colours of
    the palette in a future release, depending on feedback/registrations.
    Specifically, you wouldn't be able to change the first 4 colours (used
    for the window border and text), but the remaining 12 could be changed
    by a page-specific palette file, so that every page could have its own
    unique colours.  If you want this, tell @{"me" link autho} and I'll see what happens.
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode
@node share "ShareWare/Legal"
@{fg shine}
 >>> SHAREWARE / LEGAL
@{fg text}
 @{"Magazine" link magaz} is @{b}FreeWare@{ub}, meaning that you can distribute it anywhere that you
 wish, as long as you @{i}don't@{ui} change it!  In addition, @{i}no@{ui} commercial (ie: any
 profit-making venture) distribution is permitted, except on Aminet CD's.

 @{"MagEdit" link medit} is @{b}ShareWare@{ub}, meaning that you can distribute it anywhere that you
 wish, as long as you @{i}don't@{ui} change it!  In addition, @{i}no@{ui} commercial (ie: any
 profit-making venture) distribution is permitted, except on Aminet CD's.
 However, should you register @{b}MagEdit@{ub} by paying the ShareWare fee, you will
 receive an updated copy of it that is @{i}no longer@{ui} @{b}ShareWare@{ub}, but @{b}Private@{ub},
 which means you @{i}cannot@{ui} distribute it in @{i}any@{ui} manner; and doing so will get
 you served with a piracy-related lawsuit.  You have been warned!

 The ShareWare fee is @{b}$20 Australian Dollars@{ub}.  You can @{i}only@{ui} pay this with
 @{i}Australian Currency@{ui}.  If you don't know where to get Australian cash, try
 your local travel agency or bank.  I know it's a hassle but that's simply
 the way it is.

 One alternative to paying the ShareWare fee is to offer @{"me" link autho} a registered
 copy of one of @{i}your@{ui} programs.  An eye for an eye, so to speak.  But don't
 get your hopes up, because I'm extremely picky about what I like.  :)
@{fg shine}
 ===========================================================================
@endnode

